SIMPLE: merry
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Merry
<hw>Mer"ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Merrier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Merriest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>merie</ets>,
<ets>mirie</ets>, <ets>murie</ets>, merry, pleasant, AS.
<ets>merge</ets>, <ets>myrige</ets>, pleasant; cf. <ets>murge</ets>,
adv.; prob. akin to OHG. <ets>murg</ets>, short, Goth.
<ets>gama⟦uacute⟧rgjan</ets> to shorten; cf. L. <ets>murcus</ets> a
coward, who cuts off his thumb to escape military service; the
Anglo-Saxon and English meanings coming from the idea of making the time
seem short. Cf. <er>Mirth</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Laughingly gay;
overflowing with good humor and good spirits; jovial; inclined to
laughter or play; sportive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They drank, and were <qex>merry</qex> with him.</q> <rj><qau>Gen.
xliii. 34.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am never <qex>merry</qex> when I hear sweet music.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 915 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Cheerful; joyous; not sad; happy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Is any <qex>merry</qex>? let him sing psalms.</q> <rj><qau>Jas. v.
13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Causing laughter, mirth, gladness, or delight;
<as>as, a <ex>merry</ex> jest</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Merry</xex> wind
and weather.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>Merry dancers</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Dancer</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Merry men</b></col>, <cd>followers;
retainers.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>merie men</qex> commanded he⟦br⟧
To make him bothe game and glee.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <col><b>To make merry</b></col>, <cd>to be jovial; to indulge in
hilarity; to feast with mirth.</cd> <au>Judg. ix. 27.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Cheerful; blithe; lively; sprightly; vivacious;
gleeful; joyous; mirthful; jocund; sportive; hilarious.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Merry
<hw>Mer"ry</hw> <pr>(m⟦ecr⟧r"r⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A kind of wild red cherry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Merry-andrew</ent>⟦br⟧
